nd of monitor screen, but the laptop is a different brand.  Does anyone have any idea what the problem is here?  Is it hopeless and my monitor?  Or can I get a new graphics card to fix the problem?  Can you even replace graphics cards in laptops?  uhhhhh....Laptops that are twice as good as the one I got a year ago are now half as much as I paid!!   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/udinaekgroffgar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dinaek Groffgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/4/01 12:39:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_tongue.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Computer genius needed</span><hr size=1> just wondering...<br><br>are you using the &quot;closed-in view&quot;? You know, the one with the stone borders around everything, and one little tiny window that shows the game world?<br><br>If so, hit F10 to get to the overlay view.<br><br>the &quot;closed-in&quot; view is *forced* at a 640x480 resolution (even though you can tell it not to switch to a physicaly 640x480 it will still draw the window using the 640x480 dimensions).<br><br>The reason it is blurry at the &quot;fullscreen&quot; 640x480 is because of the LCD. LCD's are usually only able to accurately display a single resolution.<br><br>My best advice would be to hit F10 a couple times and see if that helps (while in game) <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uembermae.